# 📘 Dynamic Provisioning using NFS in Kubernetes (Documentation)

---

# 🔹 1. Objective

To implement **Dynamic Provisioning** in Kubernetes using an **NFS server**, where storage (PV) is automatically created when a PVC is requested.

---

# 🔹 2. Environment Setup

* Kubernetes Cluster: kubeadm (1 Master + 2 Worker Nodes)
* External NFS Server: Configured on separate instance
* Storage Type: NFS (Shared Storage)

---

# 🔹 3. Architecture

```
PVC → StorageClass → CSI Driver → PV (Auto Created) → NFS Server
```

---

# 🔹 4. Pre-requisites

## ✅ NFS Server

* Shared directory created: `/nfs-data`
* Permissions set:

```
sudo chown -R nobody:nogroup /nfs-data
sudo chmod -R 777 /nfs-data
```

* Export configured in `/etc/exports`:

```
/nfs-data *(rw,sync,no_subtree_check,no_root_squash)
```

* Applied:

```
sudo exportfs -a
sudo systemctl restart nfs-kernel-server
```

---

## ✅ Worker Nodes

Installed NFS client:

```
sudo apt install nfs-common -y
```

---

# 🔹 5. CSI Driver Installation

Installed NFS CSI Driver using Helm:

```
helm repo add csi-driver-nfs https://raw.githubusercontent.com/kubernetes-csi/csi-driver-nfs/master/charts
helm repo update
helm install nfs-csi csi-driver-nfs/csi-driver-nfs --namespace kube-system
```

---

## ✅ Verification

```
kubectl get pods -n kube-system | grep nfs
```

Expected:

```
nfs-csi-controller-xxxxx   Running
nfs-csi-node-xxxxx         Running
```

---

# 🔹 6. StorageClass Creation

```yaml
apiVersion: storage.k8s.io/v1
kind: StorageClass
metadata:
  name: nfs-dynamic
provisioner: nfs.csi.k8s.io
parameters:
  server: <NFS-SERVER-IP>
  share: /nfs-data
reclaimPolicy: Retain
volumeBindingMode: Immediate
```

---

## ✅ Apply

```
kubectl apply -f storageclass.yaml
```

---

# 🔹 7. PersistentVolumeClaim (PVC)

```yaml
apiVersion: v1
kind: PersistentVolumeClaim
metadata:
  name: fitness-pvc
spec:
  storageClassName: nfs-dynamic
  accessModes:
    - ReadWriteMany
  resources:
    requests:
      storage: 1Gi
```

---

## ✅ Apply

```
kubectl apply -f pvc.yaml
```

---

# 🔹 8. Dynamic Provisioning Flow

```
PVC created
   ↓
StorageClass selected
   ↓
CSI Driver triggered
   ↓
Creates folder in NFS (/nfs-data/pvc-xxxxx)
   ↓
Creates PV automatically
   ↓
PVC ↔ PV Bound
```

---

# 🔹 9. Verification

## ✅ Check PVC & PV

```
kubectl get pvc
kubectl get pv
```

Expected:

```
fitness-pvc   Bound
pvc-xxxxx     Bound   (Auto-created PV)
```

---

## ✅ Check NFS Server

```
ls /nfs-data
```

Expected:

```
pvc-xxxxx/
```

---

# 🔹 10. Application Integration (MongoDB)

```yaml
volumeMounts:
- name: fitness-data
  mountPath: /data/db

volumes:
- name: fitness-data
  persistentVolumeClaim:
    claimName: fitness-pvc
```

---

# 🔹 11. Testing

## ✅ Insert Data

```
kubectl exec -it <mongo-pod> -- mongosh
```

```
db.test.insertOne({name:"Aravind"})
```

---

## ✅ Delete Pod

```
kubectl delete pod <mongo-pod>
```

---

## ✅ Verify Persistence

* Reconnect to MongoDB
* Data should still exist

---

## ✅ Check in NFS

```
ls /nfs-data/pvc-xxxxx
```

MongoDB files present:

```
WiredTiger
collection-*.wt
index-*.wt
```

---

# 🔹 12. Key Observations

* PV is automatically created (no manual PV needed)
* Each PVC creates a separate directory in NFS
* Supports multi-node access (ReadWriteMany)
* Data persists even after Pod deletion

---

# 🔹 13. Comparison

| Feature     | Static | Dynamic   |
| ----------- | ------ | --------- |
| PV Creation | Manual | Automatic |
| Effort      | High   | Low       |
| Scalability | Low    | High      |

---

# 🎯 Conclusion

Dynamic provisioning using NFS CSI driver successfully enables **automatic storage creation**, improving scalability and reducing manual effort in Kubernetes environments.

